    },
    {
      "id": "fe8728e053d77080491997343e65653da5247d3e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2011-09-22 01:38:52.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\nThis looks good to me, but I am a bit worried about stuff in bug 6077.\nIt seems there was never total understanding of problems back then.\n\nAnyway this is good enough for subsequent testing under load and as Andreas indicated might have been only problematic initially due to ap_refresh_count sleeping, not fault handler.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "247761f7c5a3a181dfd0247eb82755613ed453dd",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 104,
        "name": "Niu Yawei",
        "email": "yawei.niu@intel.com",
        "username": "niu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-09-22 02:31:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\nI have the same concern about the bug 6077, where Andreas mentioned that grabbing lli_size_sem in page fault would deadlock the VM cleanup thread.\n\nI think you'd better ask Andreas to see if he still remember why we were trying to avoid taking lli_size_sem in page fault handler?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "524885d6319d8a8521cc13c9a323be3dc70b568b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-09-22 04:27:39.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nActually I did ask Andreas and unfortunately he didn't have this in his memory any more. So I took some time to read comment and code, and  finally I think there is no deadlock any more.\n\nIf you guys have some time, maybe you can do the same thing once again to make it sure. This is not so much clio related, anyway.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "2df2461d91010cf56ff633f214b89358e72b7619",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 104,
        "name": "Niu Yawei",
        "email": "yawei.niu@intel.com",
        "username": "niu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-09-22 05:43:39.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: No score\n\n{quote}\nIf you guys have some time, maybe you can do the same thing once again to make it sure. This is not so much clio related, anyway.\n{quote}\nI didn't see the deadlock neither.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "d523b9d1039607159053b89997bb7370533d3301",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 104,
        "name": "Niu Yawei",
        "email": "yawei.niu@intel.com",
        "username": "niu",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-09-22 05:43:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\n",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "980e8c8970dbf2a38ea34c874032331a7fd36cda",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-09-23 20:35:24.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\nI'm a bit concerned about this change, because it was definitely a problem in older kernels.  I think it needs some digging to find the history in cvs/bugzilla to determine when it was implemented, and why.  It may be that this problem no longer exists in newer kernels, but we need to know which kernel it changed in, so that we can decide if some workaround is still needed for currently-supported kernels (at least 2.6.16).\n\nIt will also need some kind of stress testing that exercises these code paths, like racer and write_append_truncate.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "e35bb7ac449844f2417204dda1d3f2defb48ee71",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2011-09-26 08:25:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nThe digging I did led me to this commit:\n\nadilger     05/04/06 18:51:27\n\n Modified:    llite    dir.c file.c llite_internal.h llite_mmap.c rw.c\n Log:\n Branch: b1_4\n Revert \"last little bit of cleanup\" for lli_size_sem locking.  Getting this\n lock (a semaphore which can sleep) in ll_nopage and/or ll_ap_refresh_count\n causes the client to lock up (symptoms include kupdated stuck, no free mem,\n client unresponsive to network = elan timeouts).\n\n Still need to figure proper locking solution here.  A spinlock is good for\n all places except for ll_setattr_raw->vmtruncate path.\n\n b=5654 (added under), b=6057, b=6059, b=6077 (possible fix)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "b069eca0fe1e83501b608f1b046ce7f95a0facc4",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-09-26 19:32:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nThanks for the comments. I didn't find it in git log.\n\nFrom this statement, it seems the original intention to not grab lli_size_sem is to avoid blocking ll_nopage by grabbing a semaphore, and clio accidently violated this. Also, this commit(5654) introduced a deadlock problem where truncate path will hold lli_size_sem and then page lock, and refresh_count path will hold page lock and then lli_size_sem, I guess the following commits fixed this problem but I didn't see it from git log. I tend to think this is the \"deadlock\" problem in the comment.\n\nHowever, from the comments in ll_get_extent_lock() at b18 branch, definitely people were worrying about the sequence of taking lock lli_size_sem and lov_stripe_lock. This is reasonable since we usually grab lli_size_sem and then lov stripe lock. The confusing part is that from commit message, it stated to avoid blocking in ll_nopage but from comment in code it stated deadlock avoidance.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "fc0b3c9c1ed9621635da99450e245ef7fa78b13a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
